WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.980 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.980 --> 00:00:02.450 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.450 --> 00:00:03.430 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.430 --> 00:00:06.860 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:06.860 --> 00:00:10.527 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.527 --> 00:00:12.360 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Last
time, one of the things

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:17.820 align:middle line:84%
we did were we proved true
mean value inequalities.

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:22.360 align:middle line:90%


00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:26.080 align:middle line:84%
So we proved true
mean value inequality.

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:27.610 align:middle line:90%
And let me recall those.

00:00:27.610 --> 00:00:35.760 align:middle line:90%


00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:38.980 align:middle line:90%
And the first one was that--

00:00:38.980 --> 00:00:45.720 align:middle line:84%
so if you had a function f on
some interval from a to b into R

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:54.520 align:middle line:84%
and this function
f is differentiable

00:00:54.520 --> 00:01:02.480 align:middle line:84%
then it said that there
exists some x0 with--

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:07.440 align:middle line:84%
x0 between strictly
between a and b so that

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:14.900 align:middle line:84%
the derivative at x0 is equal
to the average of the function--

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:18.600 align:middle line:84%
or the average of the
function at the endpoints.

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:22.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is the average
on the endpoint divided--

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:26.000 align:middle line:84%
so it's average over the
length of the interval.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:33.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is what the
mean value theorem said.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.920 align:middle line:84%
And then there was a
second mean value theorem,

00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:39.640 align:middle line:84%
and that was the Cauchy
mean value theorem.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.330 align:middle line:84%
So the Cauchy mean
value theorem.

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:52.160 align:middle line:90%


00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:57.650 align:middle line:84%
And that was where you had
two functions, f and g,

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:02.250 align:middle line:84%
on this interval into
R. And they are both

00:02:02.250 --> 00:02:04.030 align:middle line:90%
assumed to be differentiable.

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:09.330 align:middle line:90%


00:02:09.330 --> 00:02:15.490 align:middle line:84%
And then again, it was that
there exists some x0 strictly

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:18.270 align:middle line:90%
between a and b.

00:02:18.270 --> 00:02:20.970 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:33.650 align:middle line:84%
And if you take the derivative
at x0 of f times the value--

00:02:33.650 --> 00:02:38.410 align:middle line:84%
the difference in value
of g at the endpoints,

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:44.970 align:middle line:84%
then this is equal to the
derivative of g at x0 times

00:02:44.970 --> 00:02:48.390 align:middle line:84%
the difference in value
of f at the endpoints.

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:51.799 align:middle line:90%


00:02:51.799 --> 00:02:54.225 align:middle line:84%
All right, so that was the
Cauchy mean value theorem.

00:02:54.225 --> 00:02:55.850 align:middle line:84%
So it was a little
bit more complicated

00:02:55.850 --> 00:02:57.930 align:middle line:84%
than the actual
mean value theorem

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:01.890 align:middle line:84%
because you had two
functions at the same time,

00:03:01.890 --> 00:03:05.490 align:middle line:84%
and the point here was that
you can arrange this exterior

00:03:05.490 --> 00:03:08.310 align:middle line:84%
to work for both points--
for both functions.

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:16.130 align:middle line:84%
Let me just make an
observation, that if--

00:03:16.130 --> 00:03:17.810 align:middle line:90%
so if we're looking at--

00:03:17.810 --> 00:03:26.227 align:middle line:90%


00:03:26.227 --> 00:03:27.810 align:middle line:84%
so the Cauchy mean
value theorem seems

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:31.030 align:middle line:84%
like a more elaborate version
of the mean value theorem,

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:37.770 align:middle line:84%
and it really is because if
you suppose that g here was

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:41.130 align:middle line:90%
a function that is equal to x--

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:48.010 align:middle line:84%
so g of x is equal to x, I
have f here on the integral

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:51.250 align:middle line:90%
from a to b--

00:03:51.250 --> 00:03:53.470 align:middle line:90%
this is, again, differentiable.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:04:00.860 align:middle line:90%


00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:03.380 align:middle line:84%
Well, if the other
function was just

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.680 align:middle line:84%
this rather trivial
function g, of course,

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:09.420 align:middle line:84%
g is also differentiable,
and we even

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:15.260 align:middle line:84%
know that the derivative
of g at all points is 1.

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:19.100 align:middle line:84%
So if you are now applying
the Cauchy mean value theorem,

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:34.460 align:middle line:84%
then you say that by the
Cauchy mean value theorem,

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:42.940 align:middle line:84%
there exists some x0 with
x0 strictly between a and b.

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:45.940 align:middle line:84%
And so that the
derivative of f--

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:48.300 align:middle line:90%
so that's whatever that is.

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:51.460 align:middle line:84%
That's the derivative
of f at x0.

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:54.760 align:middle line:84%
The value of g at
these two endpoints

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.760 align:middle line:84%
where g is just
a function of x--

00:04:56.760 --> 00:04:59.900 align:middle line:90%
so this is just b minus a.

00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:04.940 align:middle line:90%
And the derivative of g is 1.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:11.400 align:middle line:84%
And then it's the difference
in value of f at the endpoints.

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:16.040 align:middle line:84%
And so now, if you just
divide by b minus a-- so this,

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:19.660 align:middle line:84%
of course, implies
that f prime of x0

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:26.660 align:middle line:84%
is equal to f of b minus f
of a divided by b minus a.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:28.660 align:middle line:90%
So in other words--

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:31.580 align:middle line:84%
and you see, this
here gives you--

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:35.780 align:middle line:84%
this gives you the more
standard mean value inequality.

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:38.500 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, the
Cauchy mean value theorem

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:44.140 align:middle line:84%
is more general than this
mean value inequality

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:46.180 align:middle line:90%
because you recover this--

00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:48.040 align:middle line:84%
if you just let one
of the two functions,

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:50.220 align:middle line:84%
it'd be just the
trivial function x.

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:57.150 align:middle line:90%


00:05:57.150 --> 00:05:59.830 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that was
just an observation.

00:05:59.830 --> 00:06:03.110 align:middle line:84%
The second thing I
want to talk about

00:06:03.110 --> 00:06:06.810 align:middle line:84%
is something we didn't
get to last time.

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:11.350 align:middle line:90%
And these are these--

00:06:11.350 --> 00:06:14.220 align:middle line:90%
L'Hopital's rule.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:20.030 align:middle line:90%


00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:22.770 align:middle line:84%
And I'm just going to
state one version of it.

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:27.010 align:middle line:84%
There are two versions, and
they're both in the notes,

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:29.750 align:middle line:84%
but I will just
state one of them.

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:31.510 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:33.790 align:middle line:84%
so you have-- so
the situation here

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:38.910 align:middle line:84%
is that you have two
functions, f and g.

00:06:38.910 --> 00:06:42.030 align:middle line:84%
And they are defined
on some interval,

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:50.030 align:middle line:84%
say from a to b into R.
The interval does not

00:06:50.030 --> 00:06:51.710 align:middle line:90%
include the endpoint.

00:06:51.710 --> 00:06:54.490 align:middle line:90%
So these are differentiable.

00:06:54.490 --> 00:07:03.790 align:middle line:90%


00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:08.150 align:middle line:84%
And then we assume
that the limit here--

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:13.670 align:middle line:90%
we assume that g of x is--

00:07:13.670 --> 00:07:19.310 align:middle line:84%
and not only g of x, but
also g prime of x, are not

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:22.030 align:middle line:90%
equal to 0 for all x.

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:27.550 align:middle line:90%


00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:34.390 align:middle line:84%
And then we assume that the
limit here of g of x as x

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:39.190 align:middle line:84%
goes to a, that this
here is 0, and the same

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:42.610 align:middle line:90%
holds for the function f.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:46.030 align:middle line:90%


00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:49.080 align:middle line:90%
So this here.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:51.680 align:middle line:84%
And then what you're
interested in is--

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:54.840 align:middle line:84%
what you're interested
in is that you're

00:07:54.840 --> 00:08:01.160 align:middle line:84%
interested in looking at
f of x divided by g of x.

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:03.960 align:middle line:84%
So this here makes
sense, g doesn't vanish.

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:05.620 align:middle line:90%
So this here makes sense.

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:10.760 align:middle line:84%
And you are interested in
looking at this fraction

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:16.600 align:middle line:90%
here as x goes to a.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:20.600 align:middle line:84%
If x goes to a, then the
denominator goes to 0,

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:23.760 align:middle line:84%
and the denominator
also goes to 0.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:27.060 align:middle line:84%
And the question is, does
it have a limit or not?

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:31.480 align:middle line:84%
And so there's one more
assumption here that you need,

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:37.679 align:middle line:84%
and that is that if
you're looking at the--

00:08:37.679 --> 00:08:55.280 align:middle line:84%
so assume also that the limit
here as x goes to a of f

00:08:55.280 --> 00:09:02.360 align:middle line:84%
prime of x divided by g
prime, assume that this exists

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:08.760 align:middle line:90%
and is equal to some L.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:11.480 align:middle line:84%
And then the claim
is that then--

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:21.520 align:middle line:84%
so the claim here is
that this fraction here,

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:26.720 align:middle line:84%
f of x divided by g
of x, that this does

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:36.800 align:middle line:84%
have a limit as x goes to a,
and that limit is actually L.

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:42.980 align:middle line:84%
So this is one
version of this rule.

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:45.560 align:middle line:84%
And there's another
one, very similar.

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.130 align:middle line:90%


00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:51.405 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:51.405 --> 00:09:54.290 align:middle line:90%
And so we want to prove this.

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:56.690 align:middle line:90%
So we are looking at--

00:09:56.690 --> 00:10:01.410 align:middle line:90%


00:10:01.410 --> 00:10:05.690 align:middle line:84%
so we want to apply
the Cauchy mean value

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:08.090 align:middle line:90%
theorem to prove this theorem.

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:12.610 align:middle line:84%
And so we're looking
at an interval here.

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:16.690 align:middle line:90%
So you're looking at, say, y.

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:22.630 align:middle line:84%
So here, you have
a; here, you have x;

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:27.970 align:middle line:84%
and then here, you have
y; and here, you have b.

00:10:27.970 --> 00:10:30.050 align:middle line:90%
And I'm now going to apply--

00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:31.560 align:middle line:90%
so we will apply the--

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:34.490 align:middle line:90%


00:10:34.490 --> 00:10:39.830 align:middle line:84%
so apply the Cauchy
mean value theorem.

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:50.250 align:middle line:90%


00:10:50.250 --> 00:10:55.890 align:middle line:84%
But we are applying it
on this interval here.

00:10:55.890 --> 00:11:02.330 align:middle line:84%
Between-- so y here
is less than x,

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:04.970 align:middle line:90%
but is strictly bigger than a.

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:08.970 align:middle line:84%
And this is x is
strictly less than x.

00:11:08.970 --> 00:11:12.210 align:middle line:84%
So, the function
was differentiable

00:11:12.210 --> 00:11:14.170 align:middle line:84%
on this open interval--
so of course,

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:15.650 align:middle line:84%
differentiable on
both functions,

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:18.450 align:middle line:84%
differentiable on
this closed interval.

00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:25.330 align:middle line:84%
So we can apply it-- and so
we get that f prime at some

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:44.220 align:middle line:84%
intermediate point x0,
times g of x minus g of y,

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:47.580 align:middle line:90%
this is equal to g prime--

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:50.580 align:middle line:84%
again, x0 here is some
intermediate point,

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.620 align:middle line:90%
it lie between these two.

00:11:53.620 --> 00:12:01.280 align:middle line:84%
g prime at x0 times f of
x minus g of x-- g of y,

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:05.500 align:middle line:90%
sorry, like that.

00:12:05.500 --> 00:12:10.070 align:middle line:84%
This is just applying the
Cauchy mean value theorem.

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:10.570 align:middle line:90%
Sorry?

00:12:10.570 --> 00:12:14.900 align:middle line:90%


00:12:14.900 --> 00:12:16.160 align:middle line:90%
What did you say?

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:18.360 align:middle line:84%
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah,
sorry about that.

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:19.740 align:middle line:90%
Thanks.

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:22.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thank you.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:23.300 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:12:23.300 --> 00:12:25.520 align:middle line:84%
And so now, I just
divide-- of course,

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:32.260 align:middle line:84%
this here is supposed to be a
non-zero, so I can just divide.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:48.540 align:middle line:84%
So we have that f prime of
x0 divided by g prime of x0.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:49.880 align:middle line:90%
And then I will--

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:52.460 align:middle line:84%
I want to divide
by this, but I just

00:12:52.460 --> 00:12:55.546 align:middle line:84%
need to make sure
that this here is--

00:12:55.546 --> 00:13:01.340 align:middle line:90%


00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:05.860 align:middle line:84%
that I can divide by it, that
is not 0, this thing here.

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:06.960 align:middle line:90%
So I have this.

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:15.340 align:middle line:90%


00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:22.140 align:middle line:84%
Now, think about x as being
fixed and do this for all y.

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:25.080 align:middle line:90%
If I do this--

00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:31.460 align:middle line:84%
if I do this for y where y
is very, very close to a,

00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:35.210 align:middle line:84%
this here becomes really,
really close to 0.

00:13:35.210 --> 00:13:40.230 align:middle line:84%
This here is fixed and
it's not equal to 0.

00:13:40.230 --> 00:13:44.050 align:middle line:84%
So this here is very close
to 0, this is not equal to 0.

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:47.510 align:middle line:84%
So this here, if y is
really close, if x is fixed,

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:51.810 align:middle line:84%
y is really close to a,
this is definitely not zero,

00:13:51.810 --> 00:13:53.410 align:middle line:90%
so I can divide by it.

00:13:53.410 --> 00:14:16.310 align:middle line:84%
So, for x fixed and y
sufficiently close to 0,

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:27.830 align:middle line:84%
then you have, then, g of x
minus g of y is not equal to 0.

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:34.470 align:middle line:84%
And so I get that f prime at
this intermediate point divided

00:14:34.470 --> 00:14:38.030 align:middle line:84%
by g prime at the same
intermediate point

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:48.510 align:middle line:84%
is equal to f of x minus f of y
divided by g of x minus g of y.

00:14:48.510 --> 00:14:52.730 align:middle line:84%
And now you see that's
y here goes to 0--

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:58.390 align:middle line:84%
so x is fixed still as y goes
to-- sorry, not to 0, but to a,

00:14:58.390 --> 00:15:01.250 align:middle line:84%
this here goes to
0 by assumption,

00:15:01.250 --> 00:15:04.110 align:middle line:84%
this here goes to 0,
so the whole thing goes

00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:07.590 align:middle line:90%
to f of x divided by g of x.

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:11.430 align:middle line:90%


00:15:11.430 --> 00:15:14.560 align:middle line:90%
Now the thing is that if you--

00:15:14.560 --> 00:15:18.510 align:middle line:90%


00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:21.640 align:middle line:90%
so this is for all x fixed.

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:27.010 align:middle line:90%


00:15:27.010 --> 00:15:32.470 align:middle line:90%
All right, so now if you--

00:15:32.470 --> 00:15:34.250 align:middle line:90%
so now, we want to use--

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:47.320 align:middle line:84%
so now, since f prime at, say,
z divided by g prime at z,

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:51.640 align:middle line:84%
since this fraction
here, as z goes to a,

00:15:51.640 --> 00:15:55.400 align:middle line:90%
this is assumed to go to L.

00:15:55.400 --> 00:16:02.760 align:middle line:84%
So this means that given
epsilon greater than 0,

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:06.460 align:middle line:84%
there exists a
delta greater than 0

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:19.280 align:middle line:84%
so that if z here is less
than a plus delta, then

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:20.740 align:middle line:90%
this fraction here--

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:27.720 align:middle line:84%
then f prime of z
minus g prime of z is--

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:32.100 align:middle line:90%
minus L is less than epsilon.

00:16:32.100 --> 00:16:36.120 align:middle line:90%


00:16:36.120 --> 00:16:42.080 align:middle line:84%
So now coming back here,
if you were starting with--

00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:45.540 align:middle line:84%
so this here, again,
was for all fixed x.

00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:50.240 align:middle line:90%


00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:52.140 align:middle line:90%
You had this statement.

00:16:52.140 --> 00:16:57.880 align:middle line:84%
And again, x0 was
between y and x.

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:03.960 align:middle line:84%
So now if you-- so
if this x here--

00:17:03.960 --> 00:17:17.720 align:middle line:84%
if x is-- is delta close to the
left endpoint of the interval,

00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:22.119 align:middle line:90%
then you would have that x0.

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:26.819 align:middle line:84%
But x0-- remember
that x0 is lying here.

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:35.290 align:middle line:84%
So since x0 would lie here,
this means that also, x0 here

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:40.670 align:middle line:90%
is in this interval here.

00:17:40.670 --> 00:17:44.000 align:middle line:90%


00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.370 align:middle line:84%
And so this means
that this thing--

00:17:46.370 --> 00:17:54.410 align:middle line:84%
this number here you
get is L up to some--

00:17:54.410 --> 00:17:59.470 align:middle line:84%
it's L up to some
error of epsilon.

00:17:59.470 --> 00:18:02.250 align:middle line:90%


00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:06.290 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
almost equal to L.

00:18:06.290 --> 00:18:09.770 align:middle line:84%
And so this means
that this limit here

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:15.550 align:middle line:84%
is almost equal to L
within an error of epsilon.

00:18:15.550 --> 00:18:20.690 align:middle line:84%
So this proof-- this
version of L'Hopital's rule.

00:18:20.690 --> 00:18:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And that's the second version,
and that's in the notes,

00:18:24.250 --> 00:18:28.370 align:middle line:84%
but I'll skip it, actually,
for now just because there

00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:31.550 align:middle line:84%
was-- from the last lecture,
and it's very similar to this.

00:18:31.550 --> 00:18:32.388 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:18:32.388 --> 00:18:37.453 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Why did you deduce the
g x minus g y is not equal to 0?

00:18:37.453 --> 00:18:38.370 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Sorry?

00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:39.010 align:middle line:90%
Why--

00:18:39.010 --> 00:18:41.510 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Why would you
deduce x that g x minus g

00:18:41.510 --> 00:18:43.090 align:middle line:90%
y is not equal to 0?

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:44.250 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah, OK.

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:52.370 align:middle line:84%
So this is because
g of x is supposed

00:18:52.370 --> 00:18:54.870 align:middle line:90%
to be not equal to x for all x.

00:18:54.870 --> 00:18:58.630 align:middle line:90%


00:18:58.630 --> 00:19:01.650 align:middle line:90%
And now I'm fixing x.

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:03.410 align:middle line:90%
So this here is not 0.

00:19:03.410 --> 00:19:07.330 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm letting y go
to a, but then this

00:19:07.330 --> 00:19:11.270 align:middle line:90%
here goes to 0 by assumption.

00:19:11.270 --> 00:19:13.770 align:middle line:84%
So you see that
if you're fixing x

00:19:13.770 --> 00:19:18.010 align:middle line:84%
and you just take out y
sufficiently close to a, then

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:20.730 align:middle line:84%
this denominator is
definitely not 0.

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.290 align:middle line:84%
You really want
to let this-- you

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:28.830 align:middle line:84%
want to let y goes to a because
then this here is eliminated.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:31.160 align:middle line:84%
This is not part of the
statement, that g of y.

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:33.860 align:middle line:90%


00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:36.540 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, as
long as we started

00:19:36.540 --> 00:19:41.600 align:middle line:84%
with an x that was
sufficiently close to y--

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:46.920 align:middle line:84%
if x was in this interval, then
x0 is even further to the left,

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:48.880 align:middle line:84%
so this is also
in this interval.

00:19:48.880 --> 00:19:53.160 align:middle line:84%
We don't know exactly what x0
is, but it is in that interval,

00:19:53.160 --> 00:19:56.730 align:middle line:84%
and so this means that this is
strictly smaller than epsilon.

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:59.780 align:middle line:90%


00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:01.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:01.570 --> 00:20:05.580 align:middle line:84%
So another thing we
talked about last time

00:20:05.580 --> 00:20:07.640 align:middle line:84%
was this with the
Taylor expansion.

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:13.140 align:middle line:90%


00:20:13.140 --> 00:20:15.940 align:middle line:84%
In that all of
these things really

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:20.540 align:middle line:84%
came out of this
broader theorem.

00:20:20.540 --> 00:20:26.940 align:middle line:84%
And that was also the case
for the Taylor expansion.

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:29.220 align:middle line:90%
So you have a function f--

00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:32.840 align:middle line:84%
so this is-- just to remind
you about the Taylor expansion.

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:40.940 align:middle line:90%


00:20:40.940 --> 00:20:45.500 align:middle line:90%
So you have a function f.

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:48.460 align:middle line:90%


00:20:48.460 --> 00:20:53.740 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that it's defined
on some interval here into R.

00:20:53.740 --> 00:20:56.100 align:middle line:90%
And the function is--

00:20:56.100 --> 00:21:02.780 align:middle line:84%
so f here is k times
differentiable.

00:21:02.780 --> 00:21:08.660 align:middle line:90%


00:21:08.660 --> 00:21:12.660 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
f prime exists,

00:21:12.660 --> 00:21:18.500 align:middle line:84%
f double prime up
to the k derivative.

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:19.450 align:middle line:90%
So they all exist.

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:24.660 align:middle line:90%


00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:28.820 align:middle line:84%
And then the statement
was-- so then

00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:32.420 align:middle line:90%
you looked at the k minus 1.

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:39.040 align:middle line:84%
This is the k minus
1 Taylor polynomial.

00:21:39.040 --> 00:21:47.100 align:middle line:90%


00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:55.660 align:middle line:84%
And it was given by that k
minus 1 of x is equal to--

00:21:55.660 --> 00:22:01.620 align:middle line:84%
and now you're summing here
from i equal to 0 to k minus 1.

00:22:01.620 --> 00:22:04.420 align:middle line:90%
And you take the i derivative--

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:10.500 align:middle line:84%
this is-- sorry, this is
the i derivative of f,

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:15.820 align:middle line:84%
and you do this in a, and
you divide by a factorial,

00:22:15.820 --> 00:22:23.020 align:middle line:84%
and then you're looking at
x minus a to the power i.

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:31.190 align:middle line:84%
So this was the k minus
1 Taylor polynomial.

00:22:31.190 --> 00:22:37.870 align:middle line:84%
And then the Taylor
expansion just

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:51.510 align:middle line:84%
told you that f
here at some x was

00:22:51.510 --> 00:23:02.470 align:middle line:84%
equal to P k minus 1, this
Taylor polynomial plus.

00:23:02.470 --> 00:23:06.740 align:middle line:84%
And then this is what is usually
referred to as the remainder

00:23:06.740 --> 00:23:07.240 align:middle line:90%
term.

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:13.390 align:middle line:90%


00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:19.530 align:middle line:84%
And this looked very similar
to one of these terms.

00:23:19.530 --> 00:23:26.350 align:middle line:84%
It was the k derivative
of f, but then it

00:23:26.350 --> 00:23:38.350 align:middle line:84%
was evaluated at a point c,
divided by k factorial times

00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:45.470 align:middle line:84%
x minus a to the
power k And c here

00:23:45.470 --> 00:23:50.730 align:middle line:84%
was supposed to lie
between a and x.

00:23:50.730 --> 00:23:54.190 align:middle line:90%


00:23:54.190 --> 00:23:58.810 align:middle line:84%
So that was-- this was the
Taylor expansion theorem.

00:23:58.810 --> 00:24:04.570 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is that--
so why is this so useful?

00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:08.190 align:middle line:84%
And it is extremely useful
in many different settings,

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:10.070 align:middle line:84%
also in much more
general settings

00:24:10.070 --> 00:24:12.230 align:middle line:90%
than what I'm describing here.

00:24:12.230 --> 00:24:19.470 align:middle line:84%
And that is because that if you
take a function here, then--

00:24:19.470 --> 00:24:22.160 align:middle line:84%
and it may be a very
complicated function,

00:24:22.160 --> 00:24:25.160 align:middle line:84%
but this Taylor expansion
theorem tells you

00:24:25.160 --> 00:24:32.640 align:middle line:84%
that it is close to-- if you
want to evaluate it at some x,

00:24:32.640 --> 00:24:35.900 align:middle line:84%
you can evaluate the
Taylor polynomial--

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:37.740 align:middle line:84%
that's, after all,
just a polynomial,

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:40.200 align:middle line:90%
so that's easy to evaluate.

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:44.600 align:middle line:84%
And then you get within
this remainder term

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:46.000 align:middle line:90%
of the right answer.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.920 align:middle line:90%
So that's how it always is used.

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:52.320 align:middle line:90%
And so the question is now--

00:24:52.320 --> 00:24:58.320 align:middle line:84%
the natural question is, how
well does the Taylor polynomial

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:01.930 align:middle line:84%
approximate the value
of the given function?

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:05.940 align:middle line:90%


00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:23.360 align:middle line:84%
Right, so how well does
the Taylor polynomial

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:30.790 align:middle line:90%
approximate the function?

00:25:30.790 --> 00:25:36.304 align:middle line:90%


00:25:36.304 --> 00:25:42.000 align:middle line:84%
And of course, to
understand that,

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.200 align:middle line:84%
you need to estimate
the remainder term.

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:48.040 align:middle line:84%
Let me write the
remainder term here.

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:49.790 align:middle line:90%
So the remainder term--

00:25:49.790 --> 00:25:54.840 align:middle line:90%


00:25:54.840 --> 00:25:58.680 align:middle line:84%
right, so the
remainder term is--

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:01.360 align:middle line:90%
so I write this here as--

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:06.560 align:middle line:84%
so it really depends on
x also, but I will just

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:08.480 align:middle line:90%
write it like this in here.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:12.880 align:middle line:84%
So by this, I mean
the k derivative

00:26:12.880 --> 00:26:21.890 align:middle line:84%
of f in c divided by k
factorial, and then x minus a

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:24.050 align:middle line:90%
to the power k.

00:26:24.050 --> 00:26:27.410 align:middle line:84%
So again, it depends
on really also--

00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:30.730 align:middle line:84%
of course, it depends on a,
but it also depends on x,

00:26:30.730 --> 00:26:32.490 align:middle line:90%
and it's this thing here.

00:26:32.490 --> 00:26:38.230 align:middle line:84%
This thing-- the catch is, that
you don't really know what c is.

00:26:38.230 --> 00:26:41.290 align:middle line:84%
The only thing you
know about c is that c

00:26:41.290 --> 00:26:46.170 align:middle line:90%
is lying between a and x.

00:26:46.170 --> 00:26:49.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is essentially
all you need--

00:26:49.450 --> 00:27:00.870 align:middle line:90%
all you know about c.

00:27:00.870 --> 00:27:05.050 align:middle line:90%


00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:08.110 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's look
at some examples.

00:27:08.110 --> 00:27:09.910 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at two examples.

00:27:09.910 --> 00:27:13.510 align:middle line:84%
So the first one is like
a promising example,

00:27:13.510 --> 00:27:16.570 align:middle line:84%
and the second one is
much less promising.

00:27:16.570 --> 00:27:23.570 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is that how
well it approximates really

00:27:23.570 --> 00:27:25.130 align:middle line:90%
depends on the function.

00:27:25.130 --> 00:27:32.130 align:middle line:84%
But the first one is quite
typical, though, example.

00:27:32.130 --> 00:27:35.570 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that
the function f of x

00:27:35.570 --> 00:27:37.400 align:middle line:90%
is the exponential function.

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:40.730 align:middle line:90%


00:27:40.730 --> 00:27:46.890 align:middle line:84%
And then we have that
the derivative is just

00:27:46.890 --> 00:27:48.970 align:middle line:90%
the exponential function itself.

00:27:48.970 --> 00:27:55.850 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if you
take the derivative k times,

00:27:55.850 --> 00:27:58.040 align:middle line:84%
then you just get
the function itself.

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:01.130 align:middle line:90%


00:28:01.130 --> 00:28:05.170 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
the k minus 1--

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:10.810 align:middle line:84%
which means that the k minus
1 Taylor polynomial, this

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:12.630 align:middle line:84%
is just the value
of the function--

00:28:12.630 --> 00:28:14.330 align:middle line:90%
I'll just write it out here.

00:28:14.330 --> 00:28:17.340 align:middle line:84%
So this is the value,
and now I do it--

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:21.910 align:middle line:90%
I do it for a equal to 0.

00:28:21.910 --> 00:28:24.460 align:middle line:90%


00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:27.780 align:middle line:84%
And I'm assuming that b
here-- so I'm thinking about--

00:28:27.780 --> 00:28:35.378 align:middle line:84%
I will think about this function
here f of x on this function,

00:28:35.378 --> 00:28:36.420 align:middle line:90%
the exponential function.

00:28:36.420 --> 00:28:39.060 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to think about
it on the interval,

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:54.340 align:middle line:84%
say, from minus 1 to 1
into R. Maybe I'll just

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:59.534 align:middle line:90%
take it from 0 to 1 into R.

00:28:59.534 --> 00:29:00.752 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:00.752 --> 00:29:03.940 align:middle line:84%
And the Taylor polynomial--
so I'm going to--

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:10.180 align:middle line:84%
so the Taylor polynomial, one,
also talk about that this--

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:15.180 align:middle line:84%
the Taylor polynomial
is expanded around a.

00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:18.020 align:middle line:84%
So we talk about the
Taylor polynomial.

00:29:18.020 --> 00:29:29.900 align:middle line:84%
So we talk about Taylor
expansion around a.

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:34.340 align:middle line:84%
And this just
refers to that when

00:29:34.340 --> 00:29:36.920 align:middle line:84%
you plug in a here,
well then, of course,

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:38.660 align:middle line:90%
you have exact equality.

00:29:38.660 --> 00:29:44.160 align:middle line:84%
And that all of the
derivatives are evaluated at a.

00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:46.800 align:middle line:84%
So it's really-- like
the Taylor polynomial,

00:29:46.800 --> 00:29:51.180 align:middle line:84%
it's only a good
approximation near a.

00:29:51.180 --> 00:30:00.260 align:middle line:84%
So I want now to Taylor
expand near the theorem.

00:30:00.260 --> 00:30:06.460 align:middle line:84%
And so the value here of
the function, this 1 at 0,

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:09.040 align:middle line:90%
the derivative is--

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:13.190 align:middle line:84%
so the derivative is also 1
because it's just a function

00:30:13.190 --> 00:30:14.510 align:middle line:90%
itself.

00:30:14.510 --> 00:30:16.030 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

00:30:16.030 --> 00:30:20.350 align:middle line:90%
so you get x, and then you get--

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:23.190 align:middle line:84%
the next element in
the Taylor expansion

00:30:23.190 --> 00:30:31.630 align:middle line:84%
is x squared over 2 plus x
squared over 3 factorial.

00:30:31.630 --> 00:30:36.470 align:middle line:84%
And then x to the
fourth over 4 factorial,

00:30:36.470 --> 00:30:39.630 align:middle line:84%
et cetera, up to
x to the power k

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:47.430 align:middle line:84%
minus 1 over k
minus 1 factorial.

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:54.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is the k Taylor
expansion, or k minus 1 Taylor

00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:59.870 align:middle line:90%
polynomial, around 0

00:30:59.870 --> 00:31:05.310 align:middle line:84%
And so now, if you are
interested in evaluating P,

00:31:05.310 --> 00:31:08.670 align:middle line:84%
you want to say, how
well does this here

00:31:08.670 --> 00:31:13.050 align:middle line:84%
approximate the
original function,

00:31:13.050 --> 00:31:17.050 align:middle line:84%
the exponential function, so you
want to bound this thing here.

00:31:17.050 --> 00:31:19.470 align:middle line:84%
So you want to have
a bound for that.

00:31:19.470 --> 00:31:24.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, the thing, again, is that
f of x, you know that f of x

00:31:24.190 --> 00:31:29.510 align:middle line:84%
is equal to this Taylor
polynomial, and then

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:34.630 align:middle line:84%
plus this remainder
term in the c.

00:31:34.630 --> 00:31:37.190 align:middle line:90%


00:31:37.190 --> 00:31:40.330 align:middle line:90%
Now c, again, has to lie--

00:31:40.330 --> 00:31:48.510 align:middle line:84%
c will see will lie between a
and x, and in this case, a is 0.

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.530 align:middle line:90%
So it means that c here--

00:31:50.530 --> 00:31:53.870 align:middle line:90%


00:31:53.870 --> 00:32:02.350 align:middle line:84%
so this means that c
here is between 0 and x.

00:32:02.350 --> 00:32:11.320 align:middle line:84%
And the remainder term here,
this here was equal to--

00:32:11.320 --> 00:32:16.360 align:middle line:84%
that you took the k
derivative of the function.

00:32:16.360 --> 00:32:18.720 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, the k-th
derivative of the function

00:32:18.720 --> 00:32:20.560 align:middle line:90%
is the function itself.

00:32:20.560 --> 00:32:27.400 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the value of the
s derivative, and this is at c.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:31.840 align:middle line:84%
This is the k-th derivative
of the original function.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:35.160 align:middle line:84%
And then you have to
divide by k factorial,

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:39.880 align:middle line:84%
and then it's x to
the power k like that.

00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:43.240 align:middle line:90%


00:32:43.240 --> 00:32:50.080 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that if x
here is now between 0 and 1,

00:32:50.080 --> 00:32:56.640 align:middle line:84%
this means that this thing
here, this remainder term here,

00:32:56.640 --> 00:32:59.240 align:middle line:90%
the absolute value is--

00:32:59.240 --> 00:33:04.320 align:middle line:84%
so c here is less than 1, so
this means that this thing here

00:33:04.320 --> 00:33:06.760 align:middle line:90%
is less than e.

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:12.760 align:middle line:84%
So it's less than or equal
to e divided by k factorial.

00:33:12.760 --> 00:33:15.080 align:middle line:90%
This here is bounded by--

00:33:15.080 --> 00:33:18.180 align:middle line:84%
since x is bounded by
1, this is bounded by 1,

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:21.080 align:middle line:84%
so you're getting
this inequality here.

00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:27.600 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that if k is very
large, this is a tiny number.

00:33:27.600 --> 00:33:29.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's a really
good approximation.

00:33:29.780 --> 00:33:33.040 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you don't even need to
make k very large because it's

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:34.840 align:middle line:90%
exponential.

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:36.260 align:middle line:90%
Not exponential, it's factorial.

00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:36.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:39.640 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:40.412 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:40.412 --> 00:33:42.940 align:middle line:84%
So that's a kind of
encouraging example.

00:33:42.940 --> 00:33:47.960 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that the Taylor
expansion is a very-- in this

00:33:47.960 --> 00:33:50.650 align:middle line:84%
case, it's a very good
approximation to the function.

00:33:50.650 --> 00:33:53.760 align:middle line:90%


00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.960 align:middle line:84%
Another example that
is less encouraging--

00:33:56.960 --> 00:34:00.440 align:middle line:84%
and so again, the
moral is that how well

00:34:00.440 --> 00:34:02.960 align:middle line:84%
the Taylor expansion
approximate the function

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:05.450 align:middle line:90%
depends on the function.

00:34:05.450 --> 00:34:07.970 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that
the function here

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:16.570 align:middle line:84%
was a function that was 0
here when x is less than 0--

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:18.810 align:middle line:90%
less than or equal to 0.

00:34:18.810 --> 00:34:26.290 align:middle line:84%
And when x is bigger than 0,
then it is e to the minus 1

00:34:26.290 --> 00:34:27.229 align:middle line:90%
over x squared.

00:34:27.229 --> 00:34:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:34:30.090 --> 00:34:36.210 align:middle line:84%
So you see that when x
becomes very, very small,

00:34:36.210 --> 00:34:39.710 align:middle line:84%
you are looking at
1 over the square.

00:34:39.710 --> 00:34:43.510 align:middle line:90%
So this here is huge.

00:34:43.510 --> 00:34:45.690 align:middle line:84%
But now it's with a
minus sign, so this

00:34:45.690 --> 00:34:49.250 align:middle line:84%
means that this thing
here is incredibly small.

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:53.010 align:middle line:84%
And so it's clear that
this function here

00:34:53.010 --> 00:34:55.050 align:middle line:90%
is continuous at 0.

00:34:55.050 --> 00:34:57.730 align:middle line:84%
It's clearly continuous
everywhere else.

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:02.570 align:middle line:84%
But actually, using
in this argument,

00:35:02.570 --> 00:35:06.050 align:middle line:84%
it's easy to see that
this function f here

00:35:06.050 --> 00:35:09.850 align:middle line:90%
is infinite differentiable.

00:35:09.850 --> 00:35:12.930 align:middle line:84%
So you can differentiate
it infinitely many times,

00:35:12.930 --> 00:35:14.010 align:middle line:90%
and even f0.

00:35:14.010 --> 00:35:19.950 align:middle line:90%


00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:25.770 align:middle line:84%
And by its end, of course,
the derivative is--

00:35:25.770 --> 00:35:28.510 align:middle line:84%
so it's an example of a
function that looks like this.

00:35:28.510 --> 00:35:34.530 align:middle line:84%
It's that 0 until 0, and
then it goes up like this.

00:35:34.530 --> 00:35:38.950 align:middle line:90%
And so the derivative at 0 is 0.

00:35:38.950 --> 00:35:41.130 align:middle line:84%
Any derivative,
however many times

00:35:41.130 --> 00:35:44.450 align:middle line:84%
you take the derivative
of this function--

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:50.610 align:middle line:84%
so this thing here, if
you take any derivative

00:35:50.610 --> 00:35:54.090 align:middle line:84%
and you evaluate it at
0, you always get 0.

00:35:54.090 --> 00:35:58.970 align:middle line:90%


00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:09.660 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if you're
looking at the Taylor expansion

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:10.580 align:middle line:90%
at 0--

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:16.940 align:middle line:84%
so you're looking at this k
minus 1 Taylor polynomial,

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:19.380 align:middle line:84%
this polynomial is--
all of the coefficients

00:36:19.380 --> 00:36:21.700 align:middle line:90%
in the polynomial are 0.

00:36:21.700 --> 00:36:24.420 align:middle line:90%
So this polynomial is just 0.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:27.940 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
if you're looking

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:34.660 align:middle line:84%
at f of x where f of x is
actually equal to this remainder

00:36:34.660 --> 00:36:38.540 align:middle line:90%
term, so it's somehow--

00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:40.720 align:middle line:84%
the Taylor polynomial
is too trivial.

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:43.520 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't really help
you all that much.

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:48.300 align:middle line:84%
So, it's equal to
this remainder term.

00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:50.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:50.020 --> 00:36:50.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:36:50.740 --> 00:36:53.220 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: Is there a way of--

00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:55.820 align:middle line:84%
so the remainder--
like, boundedness

00:36:55.820 --> 00:36:59.860 align:middle line:84%
helps us figure out how well
the expansion approximates

00:36:59.860 --> 00:37:01.080 align:middle line:90%
the actual function.

00:37:01.080 --> 00:37:05.300 align:middle line:84%
Is there a way to determine
how far from the point

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:06.240 align:middle line:90%
you're approximating?

00:37:06.240 --> 00:37:11.060 align:middle line:84%
Like a or 0 in this case, you
can go to a certain endpoint?

00:37:11.060 --> 00:37:13.180 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah,
right, that's right.

00:37:13.180 --> 00:37:15.080 align:middle line:90%
I mean, so you are asking--

00:37:15.080 --> 00:37:16.700 align:middle line:90%
so you're asking-- suppose--

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:18.880 align:middle line:84%
and you definitely
could do this.

00:37:18.880 --> 00:37:25.644 align:middle line:84%
You're asking-- you're thinking
that you have to have a--

00:37:25.644 --> 00:37:28.560 align:middle line:84%
you see a slightly different
situation than here,

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:30.300 align:middle line:90%
but closely related.

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:34.300 align:middle line:90%
That you have some a here.

00:37:34.300 --> 00:37:37.300 align:middle line:90%
And you have a function f.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:39.500 align:middle line:90%
And you want to--

00:37:39.500 --> 00:37:43.820 align:middle line:84%
and you are willing
to maybe look

00:37:43.820 --> 00:37:49.580 align:middle line:84%
at-- you're willing to
take some fixed large k.

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:52.540 align:middle line:90%
And then you're asking--

00:37:52.540 --> 00:37:56.700 align:middle line:84%
what I'm interested in,
how well does this--

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.070 align:middle line:84%
how well does this
function, this polynomial

00:38:00.070 --> 00:38:01.170 align:middle line:90%
approximate this?

00:38:01.170 --> 00:38:04.310 align:middle line:84%
But I want it within an
error, certain error.

00:38:04.310 --> 00:38:08.390 align:middle line:84%
So there's a given epsilon,
and you are interested

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:12.030 align:middle line:84%
in how far away can
you go from a so

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:14.630 align:middle line:84%
that this here is
less than epsilon?

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:16.790 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

00:38:16.790 --> 00:38:21.210 align:middle line:84%
so this becomes a question
of this remainder term.

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:23.570 align:middle line:84%
So this becomes a question
of this remainder term.

00:38:23.570 --> 00:38:25.830 align:middle line:84%
When can you always
say that this remainder

00:38:25.830 --> 00:38:28.710 align:middle line:90%
term is less than epsilon?

00:38:28.710 --> 00:38:30.830 align:middle line:84%
And so in this
particular case, you

00:38:30.830 --> 00:38:34.830 align:middle line:84%
would have to do it on
a case-by-case basis.

00:38:34.830 --> 00:38:39.530 align:middle line:84%
But in this particular case,
the remainder term is--

00:38:39.530 --> 00:38:44.430 align:middle line:84%
If this interval here, in
that example over there,

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:49.630 align:middle line:84%
if you have here 0, this
was a in our example,

00:38:49.630 --> 00:38:54.670 align:middle line:84%
and then you want to
go out here to some x,

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:59.150 align:middle line:84%
and now you know that C
here is between 0 and x,

00:38:59.150 --> 00:39:02.110 align:middle line:84%
but you don't really
know anything else,

00:39:02.110 --> 00:39:05.570 align:middle line:84%
so then it's like
this remainder term,

00:39:05.570 --> 00:39:10.510 align:middle line:84%
you will have this remainder
term in this example adds

00:39:10.510 --> 00:39:12.070 align:middle line:90%
this c here.

00:39:12.070 --> 00:39:14.870 align:middle line:84%
This, again, was equal
to this thing here.

00:39:14.870 --> 00:39:16.290 align:middle line:90%
Over k factorial.

00:39:16.290 --> 00:39:19.110 align:middle line:90%


00:39:19.110 --> 00:39:23.550 align:middle line:84%
And so you would have-- that
you would want this thing here,

00:39:23.550 --> 00:39:26.470 align:middle line:90%
Rk c, You.

00:39:26.470 --> 00:39:29.430 align:middle line:84%
Would want this to
be less than epsilon.

00:39:29.430 --> 00:39:33.762 align:middle line:84%
And so you would have
that this thing here--

00:39:33.762 --> 00:39:37.190 align:middle line:84%
the only thing you
can really do is

00:39:37.190 --> 00:39:40.960 align:middle line:84%
that you can say that c is
less than or equal to x.

00:39:40.960 --> 00:39:42.430 align:middle line:90%
STUDENT: And we solved for c--

00:39:42.430 --> 00:39:43.305 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:39:43.305 --> 00:39:45.290 align:middle line:84%
That whenever--
so you would do--

00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:50.310 align:middle line:84%
so what you would do here
is you would say Rk c,

00:39:50.310 --> 00:39:53.070 align:middle line:90%
this here has to be bounded by--

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:55.840 align:middle line:90%
because x c is less than x.

00:39:55.840 --> 00:39:59.880 align:middle line:84%
So this is e to the x--
you have to eliminate c.

00:39:59.880 --> 00:40:04.920 align:middle line:84%
So you would do like
this, k factorial times x

00:40:04.920 --> 00:40:05.980 align:middle line:90%
to the power k.

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:10.400 align:middle line:84%
You have to eliminate c because
you don't know anything really

00:40:10.400 --> 00:40:11.600 align:middle line:90%
about c.

00:40:11.600 --> 00:40:15.920 align:middle line:84%
And so this here now has
to be less than epsilon.

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:19.960 align:middle line:84%
So now you only have--
you have fixed your k,

00:40:19.960 --> 00:40:23.400 align:middle line:84%
and so now you only have one
variable and you can solve that.

00:40:23.400 --> 00:40:26.220 align:middle line:84%
But you really have
to eliminate c, yeah.

00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:29.476 align:middle line:90%


00:40:29.476 --> 00:40:29.976 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:29.976 --> 00:40:32.664 align:middle line:90%


00:40:32.664 --> 00:40:37.600 align:middle line:84%
So again, so how well the
Taylor expansion approximate

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:39.960 align:middle line:90%
depends on the function.

00:40:39.960 --> 00:40:43.020 align:middle line:84%
OK, the next topic is
another important topic.

00:40:43.020 --> 00:40:47.280 align:middle line:90%
And so this is integrals.

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:58.520 align:middle line:84%
And there are different
ways of defining integrals.

00:40:58.520 --> 00:41:07.280 align:middle line:84%
This here is-- this is
certainly one of the--

00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:10.720 align:middle line:90%
maybe the most natural ones.

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:15.040 align:middle line:84%
And so this is what's
called Riemannese.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So it's after German
mathematician Riemann,

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:19.980 align:middle line:90%
integrals.

00:41:19.980 --> 00:41:26.880 align:middle line:90%


00:41:26.880 --> 00:41:31.600 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is that here
now, you look at a function.

00:41:31.600 --> 00:41:37.800 align:middle line:84%
You have a function on some
interval from a to b into R.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:42.710 align:middle line:84%
And this function
f here is bounded.

00:41:42.710 --> 00:41:47.920 align:middle line:90%


00:41:47.920 --> 00:41:49.720 align:middle line:90%
And the idea is--

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:52.940 align:middle line:84%
so the idea is
for integrals is--

00:41:52.940 --> 00:41:55.560 align:middle line:90%


00:41:55.560 --> 00:41:58.680 align:middle line:90%
so you have a function.

00:41:58.680 --> 00:42:01.920 align:middle line:84%
And you want to be
able to define--

00:42:01.920 --> 00:42:15.990 align:middle line:90%
so define an area below graph.

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:18.880 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.880 --> 00:42:21.880 align:middle line:84%
So if this has a
function, you want

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:26.680 align:middle line:84%
to be able to calculate
what is this area.

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:29.840 align:middle line:90%
Now, if the function was to--

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:35.560 align:middle line:84%
if the function was to
have crossed the x-axis,

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:39.080 align:middle line:84%
then this area here
would count negatively

00:42:39.080 --> 00:42:41.800 align:middle line:84%
and this area here
would count positively.

00:42:41.800 --> 00:42:42.720 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:47.120 align:middle line:90%
So this is what you want to do.

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:51.890 align:middle line:84%
And you're always starting
with a bounded function.

00:42:51.890 --> 00:42:54.740 align:middle line:90%
Now, to do that--

00:42:54.740 --> 00:42:58.050 align:middle line:84%
right, and so you
want to define that.

00:42:58.050 --> 00:43:01.680 align:middle line:84%
The only thing that
you know for sure is--

00:43:01.680 --> 00:43:04.810 align:middle line:90%


00:43:04.810 --> 00:43:07.350 align:middle line:84%
so there's only one
ingredient you have.

00:43:07.350 --> 00:43:11.050 align:middle line:90%


00:43:11.050 --> 00:43:26.440 align:middle line:84%
So only thing you
know at the outset.

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:30.050 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:35.290 align:middle line:84%
So the only thing is that
if you take a right angle--

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:37.160 align:middle line:90%
so if this length here is--

00:43:37.160 --> 00:43:41.050 align:middle line:90%


00:43:41.050 --> 00:43:44.210 align:middle line:84%
let's call it d,
and this here is e,

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:48.490 align:middle line:84%
then you know that
the area here--

00:43:48.490 --> 00:43:55.730 align:middle line:90%
so area-- is d times e.

00:43:55.730 --> 00:43:59.250 align:middle line:90%
That's the only thing we have.

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:05.690 align:middle line:84%
So now, how do we define
the area below the graph?

00:44:05.690 --> 00:44:10.382 align:middle line:84%
And to do that, we first need
to talk about partitions.

00:44:10.382 --> 00:44:18.170 align:middle line:90%


00:44:18.170 --> 00:44:19.310 align:middle line:90%
So partition.

00:44:19.310 --> 00:44:23.410 align:middle line:90%


00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:28.370 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have
an integral here.

00:44:28.370 --> 00:44:29.950 align:middle line:90%
a and b are real numbers.

00:44:29.950 --> 00:44:32.130 align:middle line:90%
So I have integral here.

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:34.190 align:middle line:90%
Then I talk about a partition.

00:44:34.190 --> 00:44:39.330 align:middle line:90%


00:44:39.330 --> 00:44:43.150 align:middle line:84%
And it's useful to have
a notation for partition.

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:50.340 align:middle line:84%
So I call it P of
this interval here.

00:44:50.340 --> 00:44:59.510 align:middle line:84%
This is finitely
many dividing points.

00:44:59.510 --> 00:45:05.740 align:middle line:90%


00:45:05.740 --> 00:45:10.460 align:middle line:84%
And the dividing points always
have to start at a and end at b.

00:45:10.460 --> 00:45:14.140 align:middle line:84%
So you have finitely
many-- let's say k many.

00:45:14.140 --> 00:45:19.300 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking
at k plus 1 many.

00:45:19.300 --> 00:45:25.340 align:middle line:90%
So the first one has to be a.

00:45:25.340 --> 00:45:34.864 align:middle line:84%
And then you have x1 up to the
last one, and that has to be b.

00:45:34.864 --> 00:45:37.940 align:middle line:90%


00:45:37.940 --> 00:45:42.260 align:middle line:84%
And so what you
are thinking about

00:45:42.260 --> 00:45:46.900 align:middle line:84%
is-- so you have this
interval here from a to b,

00:45:46.900 --> 00:45:51.100 align:middle line:84%
and you have these
dividing points.

00:45:51.100 --> 00:45:56.580 align:middle line:84%
And you are thinking about
dividing the original interval

00:45:56.580 --> 00:45:58.780 align:middle line:90%
into these subintervals.

00:45:58.780 --> 00:46:01.580 align:middle line:90%
So these are the subintervals.

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:19.040 align:middle line:84%
So you divide the original
interval into subintervals.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:23.660 align:middle line:90%


00:46:23.660 --> 00:46:26.420 align:middle line:90%
And the subintervals are--

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:27.760 align:middle line:90%
I'll do it like this.

00:46:27.760 --> 00:46:32.100 align:middle line:84%
I will do it where I
take from-- it's always

00:46:32.100 --> 00:46:35.100 align:middle line:90%
from one to the next.

00:46:35.100 --> 00:46:38.020 align:middle line:84%
And I'll write it typically
where I'm starting--

00:46:38.020 --> 00:46:43.340 align:middle line:84%
or I'm ending at i and
beginning at i minus 1.

00:46:43.340 --> 00:46:49.030 align:middle line:84%
So I'm dividing it into
these subintervals.

00:46:49.030 --> 00:46:54.270 align:middle line:84%
So in this case here, in this
case here where this is x0,

00:46:54.270 --> 00:47:00.590 align:middle line:84%
there's going to
be k subintervals.

00:47:00.590 --> 00:47:05.450 align:middle line:84%
And you only always go
from one to the next.

00:47:05.450 --> 00:47:10.870 align:middle line:90%
So that's a partition.

00:47:10.870 --> 00:47:14.370 align:middle line:84%
And now we need a second
notion related to this,

00:47:14.370 --> 00:47:16.210 align:middle line:90%
and this is a subpartition.

00:47:16.210 --> 00:47:23.950 align:middle line:90%


00:47:23.950 --> 00:47:25.330 align:middle line:90%
So subpartition.

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:29.390 align:middle line:90%


00:47:29.390 --> 00:47:30.350 align:middle line:90%
Subpartition.

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:39.890 align:middle line:84%
This is also sometimes
called a refinement.

00:47:39.890 --> 00:47:44.190 align:middle line:90%


00:47:44.190 --> 00:47:47.470 align:middle line:84%
So a subpartition is-- so
if you have a partition--

00:47:47.470 --> 00:48:03.390 align:middle line:84%
P1 is a partition, and then P2
is a subpartition of refinement

00:48:03.390 --> 00:48:21.910 align:middle line:84%
if P2 has all the dividing
point of P1 and then some--

00:48:21.910 --> 00:48:23.150 align:middle line:90%
and then some.

00:48:23.150 --> 00:48:26.270 align:middle line:90%
I mean-- right.

00:48:26.270 --> 00:48:30.070 align:middle line:84%
I mean, of course, it could be
a trivial subpartition where

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:32.430 align:middle line:90%
P1 and P2 are the same.

00:48:32.430 --> 00:48:33.870 align:middle line:90%
That's OK.

00:48:33.870 --> 00:48:36.310 align:middle line:84%
But in general, it will
have some more points-- also

00:48:36.310 --> 00:48:37.510 align:middle line:90%
some more dividing points.

00:48:37.510 --> 00:48:42.400 align:middle line:90%


00:48:42.400 --> 00:48:46.820 align:middle line:90%
Now, right.

00:48:46.820 --> 00:48:49.820 align:middle line:90%
So now, let me look at--

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:52.840 align:middle line:90%
so what is, then--

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:57.560 align:middle line:84%
so now, let's try to get
closer to try to define this

00:48:57.560 --> 00:49:00.210 align:middle line:90%
with the area below the graph.

00:49:00.210 --> 00:49:09.112 align:middle line:90%


00:49:09.112 --> 00:49:19.000 align:middle line:84%
So again, we have a function
f from a to b into R.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:22.530 align:middle line:84%
We assume that this
is-- so that is bounded.

00:49:22.530 --> 00:49:30.240 align:middle line:90%


00:49:30.240 --> 00:49:40.100 align:middle line:84%
We have P here is a partition
of this interval here.

00:49:40.100 --> 00:49:42.680 align:middle line:90%


00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:47.240 align:middle line:84%
Then we defined a
upper and a lower sum.

00:49:47.240 --> 00:50:06.660 align:middle line:84%
Then we define upper and
lower sums as follows.

00:50:06.660 --> 00:50:09.640 align:middle line:84%
So again, you have a given
function that is bounded

00:50:09.640 --> 00:50:11.360 align:middle line:90%
and you have a partition.

00:50:11.360 --> 00:50:13.760 align:middle line:84%
And so we define
upper and lower sums,

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:18.600 align:middle line:84%
and the upper and lower sums
I will denote like this.

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:21.040 align:middle line:84%
It depends on the
function, of course,

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:22.920 align:middle line:90%
and then on the partition.

00:50:22.920 --> 00:50:24.880 align:middle line:90%
That's an upper sum.

00:50:24.880 --> 00:50:28.460 align:middle line:84%
And the lower sum, similarly,
I will denote like this.

00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:33.695 align:middle line:90%


00:50:33.695 --> 00:50:35.310 align:middle line:90%
And so how are these defined?

00:50:35.310 --> 00:50:39.610 align:middle line:90%


00:50:39.610 --> 00:50:41.320 align:middle line:90%
So they are defined as follows.

00:50:41.320 --> 00:50:44.410 align:middle line:90%


00:50:44.410 --> 00:50:50.770 align:middle line:84%
That you have-- here, you have
your interval from a to b.

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:56.170 align:middle line:84%
Then you have-- this here
is x0; here, I have x1;

00:50:56.170 --> 00:50:58.370 align:middle line:90%
and here, I have maybe x2.

00:50:58.370 --> 00:51:00.840 align:middle line:90%
And then this thing here is x3.

00:51:00.840 --> 00:51:04.930 align:middle line:90%


00:51:04.930 --> 00:51:06.850 align:middle line:90%
So I take--

00:51:06.850 --> 00:51:09.930 align:middle line:84%
I look at one of
these intervals.

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:12.310 align:middle line:90%
Well, it could be this one here.

00:51:12.310 --> 00:51:19.690 align:middle line:84%
It's between-- in this case,
it would be between x1 and x2.

00:51:19.690 --> 00:51:24.290 align:middle line:84%
And I would look at the
function in this interval here,

00:51:24.290 --> 00:51:25.550 align:middle line:90%
and I would--

00:51:25.550 --> 00:51:28.450 align:middle line:84%
so the contribution
from this here

00:51:28.450 --> 00:51:36.730 align:middle line:84%
would be that I would take-- so
for the upper sum with respect

00:51:36.730 --> 00:51:40.210 align:middle line:84%
to this partition, the one that
comes from this subinterval

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:51.150 align:middle line:84%
here would be the sup of f
on this subinterval here.

00:51:51.150 --> 00:51:53.690 align:middle line:90%


00:51:53.690 --> 00:52:02.130 align:middle line:84%
So the sup of the function
times the length of the interval

00:52:02.130 --> 00:52:03.090 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:52:03.090 --> 00:52:05.770 align:middle line:84%
So this would be
the value that--

00:52:05.770 --> 00:52:08.990 align:middle line:84%
in the upper that would
come-- in a minute

00:52:08.990 --> 00:52:11.130 align:middle line:90%
I'll write it out more clearly.

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:13.970 align:middle line:84%
But this would be what
is coming from here.

00:52:13.970 --> 00:52:21.090 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, for the lower
one, then the contribution

00:52:21.090 --> 00:52:23.730 align:middle line:84%
from this little
interval here would be

00:52:23.730 --> 00:52:32.410 align:middle line:90%
the inf of f, and then times.

00:52:32.410 --> 00:52:34.860 align:middle line:90%
And the idea is--

00:52:34.860 --> 00:52:39.100 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that would
be the contribution.

00:52:39.100 --> 00:52:41.970 align:middle line:84%
The idea, of course,
is that you have--

00:52:41.970 --> 00:52:48.460 align:middle line:90%


00:52:48.460 --> 00:52:52.910 align:middle line:84%
the only thing we knew was this
was the area of a right angle.

00:52:52.910 --> 00:52:55.540 align:middle line:90%


00:52:55.540 --> 00:52:59.180 align:middle line:84%
And so you have
this function here,

00:52:59.180 --> 00:53:02.580 align:middle line:84%
and you have some
little interval here

00:53:02.580 --> 00:53:06.060 align:middle line:90%
between xi and xi minus--

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:08.140 align:middle line:90%
sorry, xi minus 1 and xi.

00:53:08.140 --> 00:53:10.900 align:middle line:90%


00:53:10.900 --> 00:53:15.342 align:middle line:84%
And you're focusing on
this little interval here.

00:53:15.342 --> 00:53:16.800 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking
at the function.

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:18.160 align:middle line:90%
The function was bounded.

00:53:18.160 --> 00:53:20.500 align:middle line:90%
So there is a sup on this.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:24.800 align:middle line:84%
And you try to look
at the smallest right

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:30.180 align:middle line:84%
angle that kind of have
the graph that fits--

00:53:30.180 --> 00:53:32.580 align:middle line:84%
where the graph
fits inside that.

00:53:32.580 --> 00:53:36.220 align:middle line:90%
And then you're looking at--

00:53:36.220 --> 00:53:43.380 align:middle line:84%
so this is the contribution
from this little interval to p--

00:53:43.380 --> 00:53:46.020 align:middle line:90%
to the upper sum.

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:51.580 align:middle line:84%
And then you have that you're
looking at the largest right

00:53:51.580 --> 00:53:55.900 align:middle line:84%
angle like this that
fits under the graph,

00:53:55.900 --> 00:54:00.940 align:middle line:84%
and that's in contribution
to the lower one.

00:54:00.940 --> 00:54:05.740 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is that if
the function is reasonable,

00:54:05.740 --> 00:54:08.460 align:middle line:84%
if you're looking at
finite partition, then

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:12.860 align:middle line:84%
you should certainly get a
better approximation to the area

00:54:12.860 --> 00:54:13.960 align:middle line:90%
below the graph.

00:54:13.960 --> 00:54:18.820 align:middle line:84%
I mean-- and if the function
is reasonable, these two--

00:54:18.820 --> 00:54:21.860 align:middle line:90%
OK, so now what is, then, the--

00:54:21.860 --> 00:54:24.220 align:middle line:90%
let me just define this.

00:54:24.220 --> 00:54:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here, it would
be convenient to the length

00:54:31.340 --> 00:54:35.530 align:middle line:84%
of this interval to
denote it by this.

00:54:35.530 --> 00:54:39.030 align:middle line:90%
So this is xi, xi minus 1.

00:54:39.030 --> 00:54:42.430 align:middle line:84%
This is just the length
of that interval.

00:54:42.430 --> 00:54:42.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:42.930 --> 00:54:46.670 align:middle line:84%
And so now written
out, this thing-- and--

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:50.110 align:middle line:84%
OK, let me make
one other notation.

00:54:50.110 --> 00:54:59.110 align:middle line:84%
Mi is the sup of f
on xi minus 1 xi.

00:54:59.110 --> 00:55:01.310 align:middle line:90%
That's capital Mi.

00:55:01.310 --> 00:55:13.110 align:middle line:84%
And little mi is then the inf
on the same interval like that.

00:55:13.110 --> 00:55:18.310 align:middle line:84%
And so the upper sum
for this partition, this

00:55:18.310 --> 00:55:30.350 align:middle line:84%
is the sum from i equal to
1 to k of Mi times delta xi.

00:55:30.350 --> 00:55:32.510 align:middle line:90%
That's the upper sum.

00:55:32.510 --> 00:55:44.710 align:middle line:84%
And the lower sum is, then, the
sum from i equal to 1 to k of Mi

00:55:44.710 --> 00:55:46.990 align:middle line:90%
delta xi.

00:55:46.990 --> 00:55:50.710 align:middle line:84%
So that's the upper
and the lower sum.

00:55:50.710 --> 00:55:54.550 align:middle line:84%
The first thing you observe
is-- the first thing

00:55:54.550 --> 00:55:57.800 align:middle line:90%
you observe is a trivial fact.

00:55:57.800 --> 00:56:00.390 align:middle line:90%


00:56:00.390 --> 00:56:04.830 align:middle line:84%
And it really should be the
case because one is like what

00:56:04.830 --> 00:56:07.430 align:middle line:90%
fits inside the graph--

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:10.590 align:middle line:84%
below the graph, the
other is where the graph

00:56:10.590 --> 00:56:12.510 align:middle line:90%
fits below the right angle.

00:56:12.510 --> 00:56:14.230 align:middle line:90%
So you clearly have just--

00:56:14.230 --> 00:56:17.190 align:middle line:84%
and this is just-- because
this number here is the inf,

00:56:17.190 --> 00:56:19.470 align:middle line:84%
this is the sup on
the same interval.

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:28.430 align:middle line:84%
So you clearly have that L f,
P is less than or equal to U f,

00:56:28.430 --> 00:56:30.340 align:middle line:90%
P. So this is--

00:56:30.340 --> 00:56:33.040 align:middle line:90%


00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:34.180 align:middle line:90%
so this is clear.

00:56:34.180 --> 00:56:37.520 align:middle line:90%


00:56:37.520 --> 00:56:40.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:40.220 --> 00:56:46.010 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at-- let's look
at a couple of examples.

00:56:46.010 --> 00:56:52.080 align:middle line:90%


00:56:52.080 --> 00:56:56.600 align:middle line:84%
So just to make sure that
this is totally clear.

00:56:56.600 --> 00:56:58.270 align:middle line:84%
Let me look at a
couple of examples.

00:56:58.270 --> 00:57:01.040 align:middle line:90%


00:57:01.040 --> 00:57:10.920 align:middle line:90%
So the first example is--

00:57:10.920 --> 00:57:19.230 align:middle line:84%
so I take a function f of x
equal to x squared plus 1.

00:57:19.230 --> 00:57:22.040 align:middle line:90%


00:57:22.040 --> 00:57:24.720 align:middle line:84%
And my partition
and the interval

00:57:24.720 --> 00:57:29.530 align:middle line:84%
here, I'm going to think about
this as a function on minus 2

00:57:29.530 --> 00:57:41.920 align:middle line:84%
to 2 into R. And my partition
here is going to be minus 2

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:45.980 align:middle line:90%
minus 1, 0, 1, and 2.

00:57:45.980 --> 00:57:48.880 align:middle line:90%


00:57:48.880 --> 00:57:50.640 align:middle line:90%
And, right.

00:57:50.640 --> 00:57:52.480 align:middle line:90%
And so you have--

00:57:52.480 --> 00:57:53.220 align:middle line:90%
so let's see.

00:57:53.220 --> 00:57:59.360 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- so if I draw the
function, then this looks like--

00:57:59.360 --> 00:58:02.360 align:middle line:90%
if this is 1--

00:58:02.360 --> 00:58:05.720 align:middle line:90%
here, you have 1.

00:58:05.720 --> 00:58:08.160 align:middle line:90%
Then it looks sort of like this.

00:58:08.160 --> 00:58:10.200 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't-- more
or less like this.

00:58:10.200 --> 00:58:12.880 align:middle line:90%


00:58:12.880 --> 00:58:15.980 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that
here and here, you have 2.

00:58:15.980 --> 00:58:18.600 align:middle line:90%


00:58:18.600 --> 00:58:20.580 align:middle line:90%
And this here is minus 1.

00:58:20.580 --> 00:58:23.320 align:middle line:90%


00:58:23.320 --> 00:58:34.050 align:middle line:90%
And here, you have minus 2.

00:58:34.050 --> 00:58:38.690 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you're
looking at-- so, right.

00:58:38.690 --> 00:58:40.770 align:middle line:90%
So this means here--

00:58:40.770 --> 00:58:42.970 align:middle line:90%
right, so this is my partition.

00:58:42.970 --> 00:58:48.690 align:middle line:84%
So this means that x0
is equal to minus 2.

00:58:48.690 --> 00:58:52.850 align:middle line:84%
x1, that's the
next one, minus 1.

00:58:52.850 --> 00:58:56.650 align:middle line:90%
x3 is the next one.

00:58:56.650 --> 00:58:57.970 align:middle line:90%
That's 0.

00:58:57.970 --> 00:59:05.570 align:middle line:90%
x4 is 1, and x5 is 2.

00:59:05.570 --> 00:59:09.370 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course, all
of these intervals here,

00:59:09.370 --> 00:59:12.170 align:middle line:84%
they all have the same
length in this case.

00:59:12.170 --> 00:59:20.210 align:middle line:84%
So xi minus xi minus 1, this
was what we call delta xi.

00:59:20.210 --> 00:59:23.190 align:middle line:84%
This here is, for each
of these, is equal to 1.

00:59:23.190 --> 00:59:32.130 align:middle line:90%


00:59:32.130 --> 00:59:35.480 align:middle line:90%
And now, we have that the--

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:41.410 align:middle line:90%


00:59:41.410 --> 00:59:44.650 align:middle line:90%
and we have that the--

00:59:44.650 --> 00:59:48.570 align:middle line:84%
when you're looking
between minus 2 and 2--

00:59:48.570 --> 00:59:50.730 align:middle line:90%
sorry, minus 2 and minus 1--

00:59:50.730 --> 00:59:55.170 align:middle line:84%
so in this interval
here, the function

00:59:55.170 --> 00:59:58.490 align:middle line:84%
is-- the function on this
interval here is decreasing,

00:59:58.490 --> 01:00:04.570 align:middle line:84%
so the largest value is
achieved at this point here.

01:00:04.570 --> 01:00:19.650 align:middle line:84%
So M1, this is the same as the
sup of f between x0 and x1.

01:00:19.650 --> 01:00:26.980 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the same as the
sup of minus 2 to negative 1

01:00:26.980 --> 01:00:28.540 align:middle line:90%
right of f.

01:00:28.540 --> 01:00:32.580 align:middle line:84%
And the function was decreasing,
so they lie on this interval.

01:00:32.580 --> 01:00:37.160 align:middle line:84%
So the largest value is
achieved here, and that's 5.

01:00:37.160 --> 01:00:40.820 align:middle line:90%
So this would be 5.

01:00:40.820 --> 01:00:45.740 align:middle line:84%
And on the second
interval here, so this

01:00:45.740 --> 01:00:48.540 align:middle line:90%
is between negative 1 and 0.

01:00:48.540 --> 01:00:51.820 align:middle line:84%
Still decreasing, so the
value is-- the largest value

01:00:51.820 --> 01:00:54.140 align:middle line:90%
is here where it's 2.

01:00:54.140 --> 01:00:56.940 align:middle line:90%
So this here is 2.

01:00:56.940 --> 01:01:03.000 align:middle line:84%
And M3, this is now
between 0 and 1.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:06.080 align:middle line:84%
So now it's increasing, so the
largest value is over here.

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:09.660 align:middle line:90%
So that's, again, 2.

01:01:09.660 --> 01:01:13.810 align:middle line:84%
And then the last
one is, again, 5.

01:01:13.810 --> 01:01:16.400 align:middle line:90%


01:01:16.400 --> 01:01:22.900 align:middle line:84%
And then likewise, for the
ones that are the infimum--

01:01:22.900 --> 01:01:27.340 align:middle line:84%
so the first one, M1,
well, the function

01:01:27.340 --> 01:01:31.980 align:middle line:84%
was decreasing, so the smallest
value is over at that endpoint.

01:01:31.980 --> 01:01:34.620 align:middle line:90%
There, the value is 2.

01:01:34.620 --> 01:01:39.020 align:middle line:84%
So you're getting--
this here is 2.

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:46.900 align:middle line:84%
And then between negative 1
and 0, it's still decreasing,

01:01:46.900 --> 01:01:50.540 align:middle line:84%
so there, the smallest is
at this point where it's 1.

01:01:50.540 --> 01:01:51.590 align:middle line:90%
So this is M2.

01:01:51.590 --> 01:01:56.420 align:middle line:90%


01:01:56.420 --> 01:02:00.900 align:middle line:90%
And then M3, this is now--

01:02:00.900 --> 01:02:03.480 align:middle line:84%
here, the function
is increasing,

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:05.820 align:middle line:90%
so it's still the value here.

01:02:05.820 --> 01:02:07.700 align:middle line:90%
So it's still 1.

01:02:07.700 --> 01:02:14.180 align:middle line:84%
And then the last one
is between 1 and 2,

01:02:14.180 --> 01:02:17.940 align:middle line:84%
and the infimum is the
value here, so that's 2.

01:02:17.940 --> 01:02:22.100 align:middle line:90%


01:02:22.100 --> 01:02:24.720 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that in this case,

01:02:24.720 --> 01:02:29.500 align:middle line:90%
the upper for this function--

01:02:29.500 --> 01:02:33.180 align:middle line:90%
for this partition, it's this--

01:02:33.180 --> 01:02:36.080 align:middle line:84%
all of the intervals
have lengths.

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:38.140 align:middle line:84%
The small interval
have length 1,

01:02:38.140 --> 01:02:41.700 align:middle line:84%
so it's just the
sum of these guys.

01:02:41.700 --> 01:02:44.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is just equal to 5.

01:02:44.420 --> 01:02:46.220 align:middle line:84%
If you will, it's
5 times 1, that

01:02:46.220 --> 01:02:52.860 align:middle line:84%
was the length of the interval,
plus 2 times 1 plus 2 times

01:02:52.860 --> 01:02:55.340 align:middle line:90%
1 plus 5 times 1.

01:02:55.340 --> 01:02:58.260 align:middle line:84%
So in other words,
you get here 14.

01:02:58.260 --> 01:03:04.180 align:middle line:84%
And for the lower
ones, it's, again--

01:03:04.180 --> 01:03:06.600 align:middle line:90%
this time I won't write times 1.

01:03:06.600 --> 01:03:09.360 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum of those guys,
and that's actually 6.

01:03:09.360 --> 01:03:12.340 align:middle line:90%


01:03:12.340 --> 01:03:17.240 align:middle line:90%
So that's upper and lower sum.

01:03:17.240 --> 01:03:25.070 align:middle line:84%
Now-- and we had
one observation that

01:03:25.070 --> 01:03:32.390 align:middle line:84%
was an immediate observation,
and this was this thing here.

01:03:32.390 --> 01:03:39.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, what is useful
is that you're

01:03:39.310 --> 01:03:44.670 align:middle line:84%
starting with a partition, and
then you have a subpartition.

01:03:44.670 --> 01:03:46.470 align:middle line:90%
So the next one is--

01:03:46.470 --> 01:03:52.150 align:middle line:84%
so I take a function f on
some integral from a to b,

01:03:52.150 --> 01:03:53.820 align:middle line:84%
and this function
here is bounded.

01:03:53.820 --> 01:03:57.310 align:middle line:90%


01:03:57.310 --> 01:03:59.910 align:middle line:84%
And then I have
P is a partition.

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:01.890 align:middle line:90%
P1, say, is a partition.

01:04:01.890 --> 01:04:05.110 align:middle line:90%


01:04:05.110 --> 01:04:16.670 align:middle line:84%
And then P2 is a
subpartition of P1.

01:04:16.670 --> 01:04:21.650 align:middle line:84%
And now, the thing that is
useful is the following.

01:04:21.650 --> 01:04:38.110 align:middle line:90%


01:04:38.110 --> 01:04:50.030 align:middle line:84%
And so the following claim,
the following lemma here,

01:04:50.030 --> 01:04:54.030 align:middle line:84%
that if you take a
subpartition, then I

01:04:54.030 --> 01:04:59.550 align:middle line:84%
claim that the value of
the upper sum go down

01:04:59.550 --> 01:05:02.130 align:middle line:84%
and the value of
the lower go up.

01:05:02.130 --> 01:05:03.910 align:middle line:90%
So this is the following.

01:05:03.910 --> 01:05:12.870 align:middle line:84%
So, lower of f times
P1, this is less than

01:05:12.870 --> 01:05:17.960 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the
lower of f of P2.

01:05:17.960 --> 01:05:21.000 align:middle line:84%
We already proved that this
thing here, this one here--

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:23.740 align:middle line:84%
this inequality we
haven't proved yet,

01:05:23.740 --> 01:05:29.680 align:middle line:84%
but this one here we have, that
this is less than the upper one

01:05:29.680 --> 01:05:31.600 align:middle line:90%
for the same partition.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:34.040 align:middle line:84%
And the second claim
is that this here

01:05:34.040 --> 01:05:37.850 align:middle line:84%
is then less than the
upper one for the first.

01:05:37.850 --> 01:05:40.880 align:middle line:90%


01:05:40.880 --> 01:05:43.220 align:middle line:90%
Now, why is this the case?

01:05:43.220 --> 01:05:46.540 align:middle line:84%
This is also actually
a trivial statement,

01:05:46.540 --> 01:05:49.920 align:middle line:90%
but it's very useful statement.

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:54.760 align:middle line:84%
So imagine that you have
your partition P1 here,

01:05:54.760 --> 01:06:00.920 align:middle line:84%
and then you have the
dividing points i minus 1,

01:06:00.920 --> 01:06:06.800 align:middle line:84%
and here, you have i
P2 is a subpartition.

01:06:06.800 --> 01:06:10.400 align:middle line:84%
So there may be integrals
like this where there

01:06:10.400 --> 01:06:12.640 align:middle line:90%
are no further dividing points.

01:06:12.640 --> 01:06:17.160 align:middle line:84%
But in that case, your the
contribution for the lower

01:06:17.160 --> 01:06:20.200 align:middle line:84%
and upper is the same
for the two partitions.

01:06:20.200 --> 01:06:24.840 align:middle line:90%
But should there be one or more?

01:06:24.840 --> 01:06:26.560 align:middle line:90%
Let's just say there's one.

01:06:26.560 --> 01:06:31.080 align:middle line:84%
Then for the upper
one, you would

01:06:31.080 --> 01:06:33.400 align:middle line:84%
look at-- you would
then get-- so you

01:06:33.400 --> 01:06:39.960 align:middle line:84%
would get a new dividing
point, let's call it y.

01:06:39.960 --> 01:06:41.640 align:middle line:90%
And then you would get--

01:06:41.640 --> 01:06:46.760 align:middle line:84%
for the new one, you would look
at the sup here on this interval

01:06:46.760 --> 01:06:47.520 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:06:47.520 --> 01:06:51.400 align:middle line:84%
But the sup on this interval
here of the function

01:06:51.400 --> 01:06:54.760 align:middle line:84%
is less than the sup
on the larger interval.

01:06:54.760 --> 01:07:04.120 align:middle line:84%
So you would get a sup of f on
the interval from i minus 1 to y

01:07:04.120 --> 01:07:06.200 align:middle line:90%
of f.

01:07:06.200 --> 01:07:07.840 align:middle line:90%
You get that.

01:07:07.840 --> 01:07:11.210 align:middle line:84%
And then you would get times the
length of the interval that's

01:07:11.210 --> 01:07:15.210 align:middle line:90%
y minus xi minus 1.

01:07:15.210 --> 01:07:18.570 align:middle line:84%
And then you would
get a second sup,

01:07:18.570 --> 01:07:25.730 align:middle line:84%
but this is now
from y to xi of f.

01:07:25.730 --> 01:07:28.090 align:middle line:84%
And then you would
have multiplied

01:07:28.090 --> 01:07:30.110 align:middle line:90%
by the length of this interval.

01:07:30.110 --> 01:07:34.730 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
then from xi to y.

01:07:34.730 --> 01:07:38.170 align:middle line:90%


01:07:38.170 --> 01:07:43.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is what you get from the
new partition, the contribution

01:07:43.450 --> 01:07:47.090 align:middle line:90%
from the second--

01:07:47.090 --> 01:07:49.050 align:middle line:90%
from the-- this is what?

01:07:49.050 --> 01:07:50.970 align:middle line:84%
This is the
contribution that you

01:07:50.970 --> 01:08:01.050 align:middle line:84%
get from the upper sum for this
partition P2 from this part.

01:08:01.050 --> 01:08:04.010 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
this thing here,

01:08:04.010 --> 01:08:08.150 align:middle line:84%
the sup over this little
interval, well, that, of course,

01:08:08.150 --> 01:08:11.290 align:middle line:84%
is less than the sup
over the larger interval.

01:08:11.290 --> 01:08:17.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than Mi, and
I'll just keep this one here.

01:08:17.770 --> 01:08:21.130 align:middle line:84%
And this one here is
also a subinterval

01:08:21.130 --> 01:08:22.770 align:middle line:90%
of this larger interval.

01:08:22.770 --> 01:08:30.609 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than Mi
again times xi minus x, y.

01:08:30.609 --> 01:08:33.970 align:middle line:84%
But now you can
factor out the Mi.

01:08:33.970 --> 01:08:36.450 align:middle line:84%
So you're getting Mi,
and you're getting

01:08:36.450 --> 01:08:45.490 align:middle line:84%
the sum of these two, y minus
xi minus 1 plus xi minus y.

01:08:45.490 --> 01:08:48.010 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
this is exactly

01:08:48.010 --> 01:08:55.130 align:middle line:90%
Mi times xi minus xi minus 1.

01:08:55.130 --> 01:08:59.450 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
the contribution

01:08:59.450 --> 01:09:06.810 align:middle line:84%
that we get here to the upper
sum from this part here--

01:09:06.810 --> 01:09:11.100 align:middle line:84%
that was this and
this, those two things,

01:09:11.100 --> 01:09:13.380 align:middle line:84%
this is less than
the contribution

01:09:13.380 --> 01:09:17.140 align:middle line:84%
we get from the uppers sum,
from the first partition.

01:09:17.140 --> 01:09:22.660 align:middle line:84%
And so this proves
this inequality,

01:09:22.660 --> 01:09:26.260 align:middle line:84%
and this inequality
is similar with just

01:09:26.260 --> 01:09:29.939 align:middle line:84%
with the infs
instead of the sups.

01:09:29.939 --> 01:09:34.265 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is like a key point.

01:09:34.265 --> 01:09:38.340 align:middle line:84%
Each of these steps
is completely trivial,

01:09:38.340 --> 01:09:41.979 align:middle line:84%
but together, it actually
means that you can really

01:09:41.979 --> 01:09:45.420 align:middle line:90%
define something non-trivial.

01:09:45.420 --> 01:09:45.920 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:45.920 --> 01:09:50.120 align:middle line:84%
So now-- and this
may seem trivial.

01:09:50.120 --> 01:09:53.700 align:middle line:84%
Now we-- well, first of all,
we define the upper and lower

01:09:53.700 --> 01:09:56.700 align:middle line:90%
integrals.

01:09:56.700 --> 01:09:59.540 align:middle line:84%
So we have upper and
lower sum, and now

01:09:59.540 --> 01:10:02.080 align:middle line:84%
we define the upper
and lower integrals.

01:10:02.080 --> 01:10:12.860 align:middle line:90%


01:10:12.860 --> 01:10:19.480 align:middle line:90%
So upper and lower integrals.

01:10:19.480 --> 01:10:29.700 align:middle line:90%


01:10:29.700 --> 01:10:36.060 align:middle line:84%
So the upper-lower
integral-- so the upper

01:10:36.060 --> 01:10:39.540 align:middle line:90%
here is denoted like this.

01:10:39.540 --> 01:10:42.020 align:middle line:90%
We take a bar over this.

01:10:42.020 --> 01:10:44.700 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
upper-lower integral.

01:10:44.700 --> 01:10:48.620 align:middle line:84%
So this is the integral,
this is the function,

01:10:48.620 --> 01:10:51.300 align:middle line:90%
and then you write this.

01:10:51.300 --> 01:10:54.140 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
simply defined to be

01:10:54.140 --> 01:11:02.700 align:middle line:84%
the infimum over all partitions
of the upper integral.

01:11:02.700 --> 01:11:05.870 align:middle line:90%
Upper sum, sorry.

01:11:05.870 --> 01:11:10.350 align:middle line:84%
And so remember again that
if you take a partition

01:11:10.350 --> 01:11:12.950 align:middle line:84%
and you refined it,
if you're looking

01:11:12.950 --> 01:11:15.950 align:middle line:84%
at a subpartition of
the given partition,

01:11:15.950 --> 01:11:18.110 align:middle line:90%
then this number here goes down.

01:11:18.110 --> 01:11:22.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it may stay the same,
but it's certainly not bigger.

01:11:22.030 --> 01:11:28.190 align:middle line:84%
So, this is-- so the idea here
is that essentially, this number

01:11:28.190 --> 01:11:32.090 align:middle line:84%
here you get by looking at
finer and finer partition.

01:11:32.090 --> 01:11:43.590 align:middle line:84%
So, idea is that the
infimum that this

01:11:43.590 --> 01:11:50.050 align:middle line:84%
is a limit over finer
and finer partition.

01:11:50.050 --> 01:11:59.230 align:middle line:90%


01:11:59.230 --> 01:12:02.030 align:middle line:90%
So that's the idea, is the--

01:12:02.030 --> 01:12:07.030 align:middle line:84%
but the precise statement is
that it's just the infimum.

01:12:07.030 --> 01:12:09.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is the upper
integral, and then

01:12:09.430 --> 01:12:12.010 align:middle line:84%
likewise, we define
the lower integrals.

01:12:12.010 --> 01:12:15.815 align:middle line:90%


01:12:15.815 --> 01:12:17.190 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Is there
any assumptions

01:12:17.190 --> 01:12:20.110 align:middle line:84%
that you have finitely
many partitions?

01:12:20.110 --> 01:12:20.693 align:middle line:90%
Or obviously--

01:12:20.693 --> 01:12:21.610 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

01:12:21.610 --> 01:12:24.838 align:middle line:90%


01:12:24.838 --> 01:12:29.950 align:middle line:84%
But there is a key assumption
is, that for each partitions,

01:12:29.950 --> 01:12:33.270 align:middle line:84%
there are only finitely
many divisions.

01:12:33.270 --> 01:12:36.350 align:middle line:90%
But there's not a--

01:12:36.350 --> 01:12:38.650 align:middle line:84%
but there are infinitely
many partitions.

01:12:38.650 --> 01:12:41.670 align:middle line:84%
So it's really--
and so when I say

01:12:41.670 --> 01:12:45.870 align:middle line:84%
that it's a limit over
finer and finer partitions,

01:12:45.870 --> 01:12:48.850 align:middle line:84%
you should really think about
that in quotation marks.

01:12:48.850 --> 01:12:51.950 align:middle line:84%
It's not very precise statement,
but the precise statement

01:12:51.950 --> 01:12:56.030 align:middle line:84%
is just that it's infimum
over all partitions.

01:12:56.030 --> 01:12:59.310 align:middle line:90%
And so-- so--

01:12:59.310 --> 01:13:02.320 align:middle line:90%


01:13:02.320 --> 01:13:04.540 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you can
make that precise,

01:13:04.540 --> 01:13:07.880 align:middle line:84%
but then that requires
a lot of stuff

01:13:07.880 --> 01:13:10.408 align:middle line:90%
that we don't want to do here.

01:13:10.408 --> 01:13:12.200 align:middle line:84%
And there's no reason
to it because there's

01:13:12.200 --> 01:13:16.400 align:middle line:84%
a perfectly reasonable
way of defining it.

01:13:16.400 --> 01:13:18.640 align:middle line:84%
And so that was the
upper integral--

01:13:18.640 --> 01:13:19.890 align:middle line:90%
so this is the upper integral.

01:13:19.890 --> 01:13:25.560 align:middle line:90%


01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:35.520 align:middle line:84%
And then similarly, the lower
integral, the lower integral--

01:13:35.520 --> 01:13:38.610 align:middle line:84%
and there, I'm just
putting the bar below.

01:13:38.610 --> 01:13:42.360 align:middle line:90%


01:13:42.360 --> 01:13:45.120 align:middle line:90%
And you define it like this.

01:13:45.120 --> 01:13:48.520 align:middle line:84%
And this is now the
sup because remember,

01:13:48.520 --> 01:13:52.600 align:middle line:84%
that if you took a partition and
then you take a subpartition,

01:13:52.600 --> 01:13:55.760 align:middle line:84%
then this lower sum
actually went up.

01:13:55.760 --> 01:14:00.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's a sup of all
partitions of this lower.

01:14:00.240 --> 01:14:07.520 align:middle line:90%


01:14:07.520 --> 01:14:10.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:10.080 --> 01:14:10.580 align:middle line:90%
Right.

01:14:10.580 --> 01:14:13.300 align:middle line:90%
And so now we say that--

01:14:13.300 --> 01:14:14.390 align:middle line:90%
and then we say that--

01:14:14.390 --> 01:14:17.000 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:19.980 align:middle line:90%
so now, here's the definition.

01:14:19.980 --> 01:14:28.800 align:middle line:84%
And again, this may initially
seem we are wimping out,

01:14:28.800 --> 01:14:34.320 align:middle line:84%
but in a minute, we will then
determine when this is the case.

01:14:34.320 --> 01:14:38.120 align:middle line:90%
So we define-- so f here--

01:14:38.120 --> 01:14:45.920 align:middle line:84%
so if you have a bounded
function like this,

01:14:45.920 --> 01:14:58.330 align:middle line:84%
then we say that f
is Riemann integral.

01:14:58.330 --> 01:15:19.390 align:middle line:84%
So if the lower sum is
equal to the upper sum--

01:15:19.390 --> 01:15:25.650 align:middle line:90%


01:15:25.650 --> 01:15:27.000 align:middle line:90%
so if this is the case.

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:33.330 align:middle line:90%


01:15:33.330 --> 01:15:39.850 align:middle line:84%
And in that case,
and then the Riemann

01:15:39.850 --> 01:15:50.690 align:middle line:90%
integral is this common--

01:15:50.690 --> 01:15:56.010 align:middle line:84%
so the Riemann integral
is written like this.

01:15:56.010 --> 01:16:00.060 align:middle line:84%
And this is just
this common value.

01:16:00.060 --> 01:16:06.370 align:middle line:90%


01:16:06.370 --> 01:16:07.795 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:16:07.795 --> 01:16:09.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:09.650 --> 01:16:21.810 align:middle line:84%
Now, one thing I just want
to remark is that we have--

01:16:21.810 --> 01:16:25.550 align:middle line:90%
you always have that the--

01:16:25.550 --> 01:16:28.930 align:middle line:90%


01:16:28.930 --> 01:16:33.650 align:middle line:90%
so one remark is that--

01:16:33.650 --> 01:16:41.970 align:middle line:84%
so note that-- so first of all,
we had this trivial statement,

01:16:41.970 --> 01:16:45.530 align:middle line:84%
that if you take
a partition, then

01:16:45.530 --> 01:16:52.183 align:middle line:84%
the lower sum is less or
equal to the upper sum.

01:16:52.183 --> 01:16:56.860 align:middle line:84%
Then we had that if you took
a subpartition, if this here

01:16:56.860 --> 01:17:10.820 align:middle line:84%
was a subpartition of P1,
then this lower sum here

01:17:10.820 --> 01:17:16.140 align:middle line:84%
under a subpartition,
the lower sum went up,

01:17:16.140 --> 01:17:17.750 align:middle line:90%
but it's still staying below.

01:17:17.750 --> 01:17:25.860 align:middle line:90%


01:17:25.860 --> 01:17:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So you have this
inequality here.

01:17:29.340 --> 01:17:33.220 align:middle line:90%
OK, now what is this useful for?

01:17:33.220 --> 01:17:37.240 align:middle line:84%
So as a consequence
of this, we get that--

01:17:37.240 --> 01:17:40.000 align:middle line:84%
v or not the function
is Riemann integral,

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:46.620 align:middle line:84%
you always have that the
lower integral here of f dx

01:17:46.620 --> 01:17:49.090 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal
to the upper integral.

01:17:49.090 --> 01:17:52.340 align:middle line:90%


01:17:52.340 --> 01:17:54.360 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
for all functions.

01:17:54.360 --> 01:17:56.580 align:middle line:90%
And why is this the case?

01:17:56.580 --> 01:17:58.620 align:middle line:90%
This is because if you take--

01:17:58.620 --> 01:18:05.540 align:middle line:84%
this here is the Soup of
these lower partitions,

01:18:05.540 --> 01:18:10.660 align:middle line:84%
but if you take any
given partition, then

01:18:10.660 --> 01:18:16.730 align:middle line:84%
this lower thing here is
less than the upper one.

01:18:16.730 --> 01:18:21.620 align:middle line:90%


01:18:21.620 --> 01:18:27.660 align:middle line:84%
And so now, imagine
that you take--

01:18:27.660 --> 01:18:33.000 align:middle line:84%
so if you take a
lower partition--

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:34.040 align:middle line:90%
suppose-- sorry.

01:18:34.040 --> 01:18:39.620 align:middle line:84%
Suppose now that you take
the sup over all partitions,

01:18:39.620 --> 01:18:43.820 align:middle line:84%
then it means that there is one
partition so that this value

01:18:43.820 --> 01:18:45.570 align:middle line:90%
here is close to the sup.

01:18:45.570 --> 01:18:48.996 align:middle line:90%


01:18:48.996 --> 01:18:54.350 align:middle line:84%
But for this one here, you
have this inequality here.

01:18:54.350 --> 01:18:59.910 align:middle line:84%
And so in fact-- but in fact,
if you take any other partition,

01:18:59.910 --> 01:19:02.830 align:middle line:84%
you can think about-- maybe
I'll explain this in more detail

01:19:02.830 --> 01:19:04.790 align:middle line:84%
next time because I
only have a minute.

01:19:04.790 --> 01:19:09.150 align:middle line:84%
But it basically comes from--
this inequality here is coming

01:19:09.150 --> 01:19:14.830 align:middle line:90%
from this inequality here.

01:19:14.830 --> 01:19:17.710 align:middle line:84%
It will take just a few
minutes to explain it clearly.

01:19:17.710 --> 01:19:20.136 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll just
leave it here.

01:19:20.136 --> 01:19:25.590 align:middle line:84%
But a key point here is that
you have this inequality here.

01:19:25.590 --> 01:19:28.842 align:middle line:90%
And this comes from that.

01:19:28.842 --> 01:19:33.310 align:middle line:84%
But we return to that next time
because to make it really clear,

01:19:33.310 --> 01:19:36.550 align:middle line:90%
it will take a few minutes.

01:19:36.550 --> 01:19:41.250 align:middle line:84%
Now, the last thing I
want to say is that--

01:19:41.250 --> 01:19:46.590 align:middle line:84%
so you may think that we wimped
out of saying when this--

01:19:46.590 --> 01:19:48.110 align:middle line:84%
because we just
define it, we just

01:19:48.110 --> 01:19:55.435 align:middle line:84%
say that it's Riemann-integrable
if those two things are equal.

01:19:55.435 --> 01:19:56.810 align:middle line:84%
But then the
question, of course,

01:19:56.810 --> 01:19:59.670 align:middle line:84%
becomes, when are
those two things equal?

01:19:59.670 --> 01:20:01.950 align:middle line:90%
So that's the key question.

01:20:01.950 --> 01:20:09.260 align:middle line:84%
So the key question is,
when are they equal?

01:20:09.260 --> 01:20:15.910 align:middle line:90%


01:20:15.910 --> 01:20:22.270 align:middle line:84%
And we'll answer
this next time where

01:20:22.270 --> 01:20:29.260 align:middle line:84%
we will show that if f is
continuous, then they're equal.

01:20:29.260 --> 01:20:38.070 align:middle line:90%


01:20:38.070 --> 01:20:40.030 align:middle line:84%
And so anyways,
I'll return to this.

01:20:40.030 --> 01:20:46.190 align:middle line:84%
I will first-- we need,
anyway, some more information

01:20:46.190 --> 01:20:47.860 align:middle line:84%
about these upper
and lower integrals,

01:20:47.860 --> 01:20:50.920 align:middle line:84%
and I will first
show why the lower

01:20:50.920 --> 01:20:53.820 align:middle line:84%
one is less than or equal to--
the lower one is less than

01:20:53.820 --> 01:20:55.680 align:middle line:84%
or equal to the
upper one always.

01:20:55.680 --> 01:20:58.960 align:middle line:84%
And then we will talk
about some criteria

01:20:58.960 --> 01:21:00.420 align:middle line:90%
for when they are equal.

01:21:00.420 --> 01:21:03.560 align:middle line:84%
And then we will prove this
for continuous functions.

01:21:03.560 --> 01:21:05.852 align:middle line:84%
STUDENT: Is that an if and
only if or are there other--

01:21:05.852 --> 01:21:06.643 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: No.

01:21:06.643 --> 01:21:07.160 align:middle line:90%
No, no, no.

01:21:07.160 --> 01:21:07.660 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:21:07.660 --> 01:21:09.160 align:middle line:90%
It's not.

01:21:09.160 --> 01:21:12.800 align:middle line:90%
It's not-- it's--

01:21:12.800 --> 01:21:15.480 align:middle line:90%
yeah, it's not a total answer.

01:21:15.480 --> 01:21:20.200 align:middle line:84%
It's a good initial
answer, but there

01:21:20.200 --> 01:21:24.720 align:middle line:84%
are many functions that are not
continuous that are very worth--

01:21:24.720 --> 01:21:31.440 align:middle line:84%
that plays key roles,
and they're still--

01:21:31.440 --> 01:21:33.390 align:middle line:84%
and we will also
look at an example--

01:21:33.390 --> 01:21:35.140 align:middle line:84%
it's in the notes, but
I didn't get to it,

01:21:35.140 --> 01:21:40.720 align:middle line:84%
we look at an example of
function that is not--

01:21:40.720 --> 01:21:43.520 align:middle line:84%
where you don't
have this equality.

01:21:43.520 --> 01:21:45.990 align:middle line:90%
And this is like an old.

01:21:45.990 --> 01:21:48.000 align:middle line:90%